
1. Clearly separate BigNat from Integer/Natural

2. Integer and Natural use BigNat primitives and type

3. We have several BigNat backends:
   * GMP: based on GMP library (adapted from integer-gmp)
   * Native: brand new implementation built from scratch
   * FFI: implementation that relies on FFI calls. This backend is useful for
     alternative GHC backends that target non native platforms (e.g. GHCJS
     targets JavaScript's BigInt: it would just have to replace BigNat FFI calls
     appropriately during code generation).
   * Note that Simple backend (from integer-simple) is gone as it was a pain to
     adapt to the new BigNat interface and as it was slower than the newer
     Native backend (which code is quite simple to understand too)

4. New backends are easier to add
   * The BigNat interface is much simpler than the whole Integer/Natural one
   * FFI backend can be used to try new backends: just link with an object
     exporting the expected bignat symbols.

5. The compiler only knows about Integer and Natural representation
   * it is the same with all the BigNat backends so we can remove backend
     specific hacks in the compiler
   * optimization rules that were only available with integer-gmp are now always
     available.

6. The code of the Native backend has the same license as GHC.

